Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class HasInstrumentIdMap<T extends HasInstrumentId,​V>

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.HasLongMap<InstrumentId,​Pair<T,​V>>
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.HasInstrumentIdMap<T,​V>
public class HasInstrumentIdMap<T extends HasInstrumentId,​V>
extends HasLongMap<InstrumentId,​Pair<T,​V>>
A map of HasInstrumentId to some type V.

Upside: it uses the instrument-id-specific optimized maps (using GNU Trove).

Downside: you only index the map using an InstrumentId, not the full HasInstrumentId class. However, that's not bad, since we rarely implement #equals, and we'd need to if we actually wanted to use the HasInstrumentId as a key.

This is useful for cases where we want to attach additional information to the InstrumentId, without generating 2 maps of iid -> HasInstrumentId and iid -> value.

See Also:

    • transformedStream

      public <T2> java.util.stream.Stream<T2> transformedStream​(java.util.function.BiFunction<T,​V,​T2> biFunction)
      We could have exposed an entrySet() (to fit with map conventions) but that would need to expose the Pair<T, V>, and it would be confusing since the key in the map is still the instrument ID, not the entire HasInstrumentId itself.

      By only exposing a stream of the contents of this map after each entry is transformed, we can avoid that. There's no mention of a pair below.

      public IidMap<V> toIidMap()
      Converts to an IidMap by only keeping the InstrumentId portion of the HasInstrumentId key. Of course, the resulting IidMap will not have enough information in it to let us convert back to this HasInstrumentIdPartition.
